== Story ==
As the Earth-elemental [[Four Fiends (Final Fantasy)|fiend]], Lich drains the power of the [[Earth Crystal (term)|Earth Crystal]], rotting the soil in [[Melmond]]. Lich was the third fiend to awaken, doing so shortly before the [[Warriors of Light]] set out on their quest. When the Warriors arrive in Melmond, they find the earth rotting and people dying. They learn a that [[Vampire (Final Fantasy)|vampire]] is being blamed and travel into the nearby Cavern of Earth to defeat it, but upon returning to the [[town]], they see the earth is still decaying.

Using the Star Ruby found in the cavern to gain passage through the [[Giant's Cave]], they travel to the [[Sage's Cave]], where they are told by [[Sadda (Final Fantasy)|Sadda]] that the vampire was only working for a greater force: Lich. The Warriors return to the Cavern of Earth, where they find the Earth Crystal. After confronting Lich, the party prevails. The Earth Crystal shines again and the land rots no more.

Later, the Warriors fight a younger version of the Lich in the Chaos Shrine 2000 years in the past. They defeat him once more, preventing him from journeying to the future and causing the earth to rot in the first place.

== Battle ==
=== First battle ===
[[File:FF1_3DS_Lich_Location.jpg|thumb|left|Lich's location]]
Lich is the hardest boss faced at that point in the game. As an undead enemy, he is weak to [[Dia (Final Fantasy)|Dia]] and [[Fire (Final Fantasy element)|Fire]]. Lich's physical blows have a chance to [[Paralysis (Final Fantasy)|paralyze]] whomever it hits. Lich uses elemental and debilitating spells and can complement his physical prowess with Haste.

==== Strategy ====
[[Fira (Final Fantasy)|Fira]] and [[Firaga (Final Fantasy)|Firaga]] (if available) are effective. [[Attack (command)|Physical attacks]] on their own will not be very effective; they should be augmented with [[Haste (Final Fantasy)|Haste]] and/or [[Temper (Final Fantasy)|Temper]].

It is recommended to use the spells [[NulFrost (Final Fantasy)|NulFrost]], [[NulShock (Final Fantasy)|NulShock]], and [[NulBlaze (Final Fantasy)|NulBlaze]] to halve the damage from Lich's elemental spells. The party should increase evasion with [[Invis (Final Fantasy)|Invis]] or [[Blink (Final Fantasy)|Blink]] to avoid his powerful physical blows and decrease the chance of getting paralyzed.

From ''[[Final Fantasy I & II: Dawn of Souls|Dawn of Souls]]'' to ''[[Final Fantasy 20th Anniversary|20th Anniversary Edition]]'', the player can also use [[Red Fang (Final Fantasy)|Red Fangs]] for damage dealing and the [[White Curtain]], [[Blue Curtain]], and [[Red Curtain]] to cast the Nul- spells for protection instead of casting the spells.

In the NES version, a lucky pair of shots with Firaga and [[Diaga (Final Fantasy)|Diaga]] can, potentially, kill Lich in one round (as the spells do extra damage to undead and both have high-end damage at or over 200, while Lich only has 400 HP) or at least leave him in a state where one more round of spells will assuredly kill him. This tactic is less advisable in later versions, as Lich's HP has increased greatly.

=== Second battle ===
When the Warriors of Light [[Time travel|travel through time]], they must fight the Lich of the past. His floor of the Chaos Shrine contains many of the monsters from the Cavern of Earth and the stairway to the next floor is guarded by the past Lich, a [[fixed encounter]]. Prior to ''[[Pixel Remaster]]'', the battle can be repeatedly triggered by walking through the same spots.

His stats are improved and his spell list uses only level 8 black magic. Lich also loses his weakness to fire.
==== Strategy ====
Everyone should resist [[Time (Final Fantasy)|time]] and [[Instant Death (Final Fantasy)|instant death]] elements. Physical attacks should be augmented with Haste, Temper, and [[Saber (Final Fantasy ability)|Saber]]. [[White Mage (Final Fantasy)|White Mages/Wizards]] should cast [[Diaga (Final Fantasy)|Diaga]] or [[Diaja (Final Fantasy)|Diaja]], while [[Black Mage (Final Fantasy)|Black Mages/Wizards]] should use [[Thundaga (Final Fantasy)|Thundaga]] or [[Flare (Final Fantasy)|Flare]]. For versions that use a spell charge system rather than MP, players may wish to hold off on attack magic to conserve their spell charges, as Lich is only the first of several upcoming boss fights and there is no way to replenish charges while inside the dungeon.
